    question: "Explain the difference between horizontal and vertical scaling. When would you choose one over the other?",
    hint: "Think about cost curves, statelessness, database constraints, and ceiling limits.",
    keyPoints: ["Vertical: bigger machine, simpler but has ceiling", "Horizontal: more machines, requires stateless design", "Database vertical scaling often cheaper up to a point", "Horizontal needs load balancer and session management", "Cost vs complexity trade-off"],
    modelAnswer: `**Vertical Scaling (Scale Up)**: Replace server with a larger one — more CPU cores, RAM, faster SSD. Example: upgrade from 4-core/16GB to 64-core/512GB instance. Pros: No code changes needed, no distributed complexity. Cons: Hard ceiling (largest AWS instance ~24TB RAM, 448 vCPUs), single point of failure, downtime during upgrade. **Horizontal Scaling (Scale Out)**: Add more machines behind a load balancer. All instances run the same application. Pros: No theoretical ceiling, fault tolerant (one node failure = ~1% capacity loss), cloud-native elastic scaling. Cons: Requires stateless services (sessions in Redis), distributed consistency challenges, higher operational complexity. **Decision Framework**: Start vertical: simpler, cheaper at low scale. Switch to horizontal when: vertical ceiling is hit, HA requirements, geographic distribution needed. Databases: vertical scaling works longer. PostgreSQL on RDS r6g.16xlarge (512GB RAM) handles most apps. Stateless API servers: horizontal from the start. **Hybrid approach** (most real systems): Vertical for stateful components (DB primary), horizontal for stateless components (API servers, workers).`,
