    type: "technical",
    difficulty: "Medium",
    question: "What is the CAP theorem? Give a concrete example of a CP system and an AP system and explain the trade-offs.",
    hint: "Define Consistency, Availability, Partition tolerance. Explain why partition tolerance is non-negotiable in distributed systems.",
    keyPoints: ["Partition tolerance is mandatory in distributed systems", "CP sacrifices availability during partition", "AP sacrifices strong consistency", "Eventual consistency in AP systems", "Real systems tune consistency level per operation"],
    modelAnswer: `**CAP Theorem**: A distributed system can guarantee at most 2 of 3 properties simultaneously. Consistency: Every read receives the most recent write or an error — all nodes see same data. Availability: Every request receives a non-error response, though may not be most recent data. Partition Tolerance: System continues operating even when network partitions prevent some nodes from communicating. **Why P is non-negotiable**: In any real distributed system, network partitions will happen. The real choice is CP vs AP during a partition. **CP System — ZooKeeper, HBase, etcd**: During a partition, the minority partition refuses reads and writes to maintain consistency. ZooKeeper: if a quorum cannot be reached, the service becomes unavailable rather than returning stale data. Use case: distributed locks, leader election, configuration management. **AP System — Cassandra, CouchDB, DynamoDB (default)**: During a partition, all nodes remain available and accept reads and writes. Nodes in the minority partition serve potentially stale data. After partition heals: reconcile via eventual consistency (last-write-wins, vector clocks, CRDTs). Use case: shopping cart, DNS, social media feeds where availability trumps momentary inconsistency. **Tunable consistency**: Cassandra allows per-query consistency: QUORUM (CP-ish), ONE (AP-ish). DynamoDB: strongly consistent reads (CP) or eventually consistent reads (AP, half the cost).`,
