    difficulty: "Hard",
    question: "Explain database sharding strategies. Compare range-based, hash-based, and directory-based sharding. What problems does sharding introduce?",
    hint: "Cover data distribution, hotspots, cross-shard queries, resharding complexity, and the application-layer vs middleware approach.",
    keyPoints: ["Range sharding: hotspots but range queries easy", "Hash sharding: even distribution, range queries hard", "Directory sharding: flexible but lookup service is SPOF", "Cross-shard joins and transactions are expensive", "Resharding cost is significant"],
    modelAnswer: `**Why Shard?** Single DB node limit: ~10TB data, ~100K QPS. Beyond this, shard horizontally. **Range-Based Sharding**: Shard by value range: user_id 1-1M on shard 1, 1M-2M on shard 2. Pros: Range queries efficient. Cons: Hotspots — new users all go to last shard. Uneven load if access patterns skew recent data. **Hash-Based Sharding**: shard = hash(shard_key) % N. Pros: No hotspots, uniform load. Cons: Range queries require hitting all shards. Resharding remaps ~(N-1)/N of all keys. Fix: Consistent hashing reduces resharding cost to 1/N. **Directory-Based Sharding**: Lookup service maps keys to shards. Pros: Maximum flexibility, easy rebalancing by updating directory. Cons: Lookup service is a SPOF and performance bottleneck. Must be cached aggressively. **Problems Sharding Introduces**: (1) Cross-shard joins: must fetch separately and join in application code. (2) Cross-shard transactions: 2PC needed (expensive, complex). (3) Hot keys: celebrity user on one shard overloads it — sub-shard or move hot records. (4) Resharding: requires migrating data — expensive downtime or complex live migration. (5) Schema changes: must apply migrations to all shards simultaneously. **Choosing shard key**: High cardinality, evenly distributed, query-aligned to avoid scatter-gather. **Capacity example**: 100 shards, each PostgreSQL on r6g.xlarge (32GB RAM, 4 vCPU) gives 1TB total RAM, 400 vCPU pool, ~10M QPS aggregate.`,
