    difficulty: "Hard",
    question: "Compare Kafka, RabbitMQ, and AWS SQS for message queue use cases. When would you choose each?",
    hint: "Cover throughput, ordering, replay, routing flexibility, operational complexity, and delivery guarantees.",
    keyPoints: ["Kafka: high throughput, replay, event streaming", "RabbitMQ: flexible routing, complex topologies", "SQS: managed, simple, no replay", "Consumer groups vs competing consumers", "Ordering guarantees differ across all three"],
    modelAnswer: `**Apache Kafka**: Distributed commit log. Topics split into partitions with ordered, immutable messages indexed by offset. Throughput: Millions of messages per second via sequential disk writes and zero-copy transfer. Messages retained for days or weeks — consumers can re-read from any offset enabling event sourcing and reprocessing. Ordering guaranteed within a partition, not across partitions. Consumer Groups: Each group independently reads all partitions so multiple applications can consume the same topic. Use when: event streaming, analytics pipelines, log aggregation, event sourcing, Change Data Capture. Operational complexity: High — brokers, ZooKeeper or KRaft, topic management, monitoring consumer lag. **RabbitMQ**: Message broker with exchanges, queues, bindings. AMQP protocol. Routing: direct, fanout, topic, header exchanges. Throughput: ~50K-100K msg/sec. Messages deleted after consumption (no replay). Use when: complex routing logic, task queues, RPC patterns, moderate throughput, transactional messaging. **AWS SQS**: Fully managed, zero operational overhead. Standard: at-least-once delivery, best-effort ordering, nearly unlimited throughput. FIFO: exactly-once, ordered, 3,000 msg/sec with batching. Dead Letter Queue for failed messages. Use when: AWS-native workloads, decoupling microservices, simple work queues, zero ops burden desired. **Decision**: Need replay or event sourcing: Kafka. Complex routing: RabbitMQ. AWS serverless, simple, fully managed: SQS. Multi-team event bus: Kafka (each team has its own consumer group).`,
