    modelAnswer: `**PostgreSQL strengths**:
- Full SQL standard compliance (FULL OUTER JOIN, CTEs, window functions, LATERAL).
- Advanced data types: arrays, JSONB (indexed), hstore, range types, UUID, ENUM.
- Powerful indexing: partial indexes, expression indexes, GIN (full-text, JSONB), GiST (geospatial).
- Table inheritance, row-level security, foreign data wrappers (query external data sources).
- MVCC: readers never block writers; no table-level read locks.
- Better for complex analytical queries, geospatial (PostGIS), full-text search.

**MySQL strengths**:
- Historically faster for simple primary-key lookups and read-heavy workloads (benchmarks vary by version).
- Wider managed hosting support (RDS MySQL, PlanetScale, managed options on nearly every provider).
- Simpler setup and configuration for smaller teams.
- Binary replication is mature and well-documented.
- InnoDB clustered index: rows stored in PK order — very fast PK lookups and range scans.

**Key technical differences**:
| Feature | PostgreSQL | MySQL InnoDB |
|---|---|---|
| MVCC | No-overwrite (needs VACUUM) | Undo log (in-place update) |
| Primary key | Heap files + separate indexes | Clustered index (rows stored by PK) |
| FULL OUTER JOIN | Yes | No (emulate with UNION) |
| JSONB | Indexed binary JSON | JSON (string stored, limited indexing) |
| Stored procedures | PL/pgSQL, PL/Python, PL/V8 | T-SQL-like syntax |

**Choose PostgreSQL**: complex queries, JSONB storage, geospatial, strict SQL compliance, advanced analytics.
**Choose MySQL**: existing MySQL ecosystem, simpler workloads, specific managed service requirements.`,
