    domain: "Manual Testing",
    type: "technical",
    difficulty: "Medium",
    question: "What is Equivalence Partitioning? How do you derive test cases using this technique? Give a worked example.",
    hint: "Divide input data into partitions where all values behave identically. Test one representative value per partition instead of every value.",
    keyPoints: [
      "Valid and invalid partitions",
      "Reduces test cases without losing coverage",
      "One representative value per class",
      "Combine with BVA for maximum efficiency",
    ],
    modelAnswer: `Equivalence Partitioning (EP) divides the input domain into groups where the software behaves identically for all values in that group. You test one representative value per class instead of every possible value.

Rules:
- Range condition (e.g. 1-100): three classes — below range (invalid), within range (valid), above range (invalid)
- Set condition (e.g. Red, Green, Blue): two classes — member of set (valid), not a member (invalid)

Worked Example — Age field on a discount website:
Business rule: 18-60 = standard discount; 61+ = senior discount; <18 = rejected.

  Partition | Range | Test Value | Expected
  Invalid   | <18   | 10         | Rejected
  Standard  | 18-60 | 35         | Standard discount
  Senior    | 61+   | 70         | Senior discount

Result: 3 test cases instead of testing every age from 0 to 120+.

In practice: Apply EP to every input field — text length (too short / valid / too long), numeric ranges, dropdown options, file upload types. Always combine with Boundary Value Analysis for maximum coverage with minimum test cases.`,
