    modelAnswer: `Standard Test Case Template:

  Field            | Example
  Test Case ID     | TC_CART_003
  Title            | Add item to cart as a guest user
  Module           | Shopping Cart
  Requirement ID   | US-45
  Priority         | High
  Preconditions    | User NOT logged in; product ABC-123 in stock (qty > 0)
  Test Steps       | 1. Open product page  2. Click "Add to Cart"
  Test Data        | SKU: ABC-123, Quantity: 1
  Expected Result  | Login prompt shown; item retained in cart after login
  Actual Result    | (filled during execution)
  Status           | Pass / Fail / Blocked
  Tester / Date    | Filled at execution time

Qualities of a genuinely useful test case:
1. Atomic: one scenario — immediately clear what failed
2. Unambiguous: any two testers following the steps independently get the same result
3. Specific expected result: "Error 'Invalid credentials' below the password field" — NOT "an error appears"
4. Traceable: linked to a requirement ID so stakeholders can verify coverage
5. Independent: runnable in any order without another test case needing to pass first
6. Repeatable: same steps + same data = same result, regardless of who runs it

Common mistakes:
- Vague expected results ("it should work", "data should be saved")
- Missing preconditions (test fails due to wrong setup, not an actual defect)
- Steps assuming unstated knowledge ("configure the environment appropriately")
- Testing multiple conditions in one case (impossible to identify which caused the failure)`,
