    modelAnswer: `In Agile, QA is embedded in the cross-functional sprint team from day one. Testing happens within the sprint alongside development.

Sprint Ceremonies — QA Participation:

  Sprint Planning (Day 1):
  Review all user stories, validate acceptance criteria are clear and testable, estimate testing effort, identify test data and environment dependencies, flag ambiguous stories before development starts.

  Daily Standup:
  Report: what was tested yesterday, what is being tested today, any blockers (build not deployed, environment down, dependency still in progress).

  Backlog Refinement (mid-sprint):
  Participate in Three Amigos sessions, raise edge cases and missing ACs, ensure stories are written with testability in mind.

  Sprint Review / Demo:
  Confirm tested features work as demonstrated. Report defect status: all Critical/High closed? Any deferred?

  Sprint Retrospective:
  Contribute: what testing went well, what slowed down, what to try differently next sprint.

Three Amigos:
  Pre-development meeting: Business Analyst + Developer + QA Tester review one user story before coding begins.
  - BA:        explains business intent and acceptance criteria
  - Developer: asks technical implementation questions
  - QA:        asks about edge cases, error paths, and how each AC is verifiable
  Goal: All three have identical understanding before a single line of code is written.
  Prevents the situation where developer, tester, and BA each interpreted the story differently.

Definition of Done (DoD):
  Team-agreed non-negotiable checklist every story must satisfy to be called Done:
  - Code complete and peer code-reviewed
  - Unit tests written and passing in CI
  - Feature deployed to test environment
  - QA test cases written and all executed
  - All Critical/High defects resolved and verified
  - All acceptance criteria verified by QA
  - Product Owner approved the feature
  - Documentation updated where required
  A story is NOT Done until every item is satisfied — no partial credit.`,
