    question: "What is accessibility testing? What are WCAG guidelines and how do you test for accessibility compliance?",
    hint: "Accessibility testing verifies the product is usable by people with disabilities. WCAG 2.1 defines four principles: Perceivable, Operable, Understandable, Robust (POUR).",
    keyPoints: [
      "WCAG 2.1 levels: A (minimum), AA (standard), AAA (enhanced)",
      "POUR principles: Perceivable, Operable, Understandable, Robust",
      "Test with screen readers (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver)",
      "Keyboard-only navigation testing",
      "Tools: axe, Lighthouse, WAVE",
    ],
    modelAnswer: `Accessibility Testing verifies that people with disabilities can perceive, operate, understand, and interact with the product.

WCAG 2.1 — Web Content Accessibility Guidelines:
Organised around four principles (POUR):

Perceivable: Information must be presentable in ways users can perceive.
- Every image must have an alt attribute describing its content
- Videos must have captions
- Text must have sufficient colour contrast (minimum 4.5:1 ratio for normal text — Level AA)
- Content must not rely on colour alone to convey meaning

Operable: UI components must be operable.
- All functionality must be accessible via keyboard alone (no mouse required)
- No keyboard traps (focus must not become stuck in a component)
- Users must have enough time to read and use content (no auto-expiring sessions without warning)
- No content that flashes more than 3 times per second (seizure risk)

Understandable: Information and UI operation must be understandable.
- Form fields must have associated labels (not just placeholder text)
- Error messages must identify the field in error and suggest the correct format
- Page language must be set in the HTML lang attribute

Robust: Content must be robust enough for assistive technologies to interpret.
- Valid, semantic HTML (headings structured as h1→h2→h3, not skipped)
- ARIA labels used correctly for custom components (date pickers, modals, tabs)

Compliance levels: A (minimum), AA (required by most laws, e.g. UK PSBAR, US Section 508), AAA (enhanced — aspirational).

How to test:
1. Automated scan: Run axe, Lighthouse, or WAVE to catch approximately 30-40% of issues automatically
2. Keyboard-only navigation: Tab through the entire application — can every interactive element be reached and activated with keyboard alone?
3. Screen reader testing: Use NVDA (free, Windows), JAWS (Windows), or VoiceOver (macOS/iOS) and navigate the application as a blind user would
4. Colour contrast checker: Use the Colour Contrast Analyser tool on all text elements
5. Zoom test: Zoom browser to 200% — does layout remain usable with no horizontal scroll?`,
