    difficulty: "Hard",
    question: "You are given 2 days to test a complex feature that normally requires 5 days. How do you prioritise your testing?",
    hint: "Apply risk-based testing: identify the highest-risk areas, test critical paths first, document what is not tested, and communicate the residual risk clearly to stakeholders.",
    keyPoints: [
      "Identify highest-risk areas and core business flows",
      "Test in priority order: Critical/High first",
      "Document what you are NOT testing and why",
      "Communicate residual risk to the team and management",
      "Use smoke test and key regression cases — skip low-risk edge cases",
    ],
    modelAnswer: `2 Days for 5 Days of Testing — Risk-Based Prioritisation Approach:

Step 1: Immediately communicate the constraint.
Inform the Test Lead, Project Manager, and Product Owner that with 2 days you can cover approximately 40% of the planned test scope. Get acknowledgement in writing so the residual risk is formally accepted.

Step 2: Prioritise ruthlessly using risk-based testing.
With the available time, test in this order:

Priority 1 — Critical business flows (MUST test):
The core end-to-end scenarios that represent the most common and most business-critical user journeys. If these fail, the feature cannot ship. Test these first, thoroughly, with positive and key negative cases.

Priority 2 — High-risk areas (test with available time):
Areas of the feature that are new, complex, recently changed, or have historically had bugs. Cover positive + key negative cases.

Priority 3 — Medium-risk (test if time allows):
Secondary flows, edge cases, non-critical UI elements.

Priority 4 — Low-risk (explicitly skip and document):
Visual-only changes, low-frequency edge cases, areas unchanged from previous working version.

Step 3: Modify the test suite, do not try to rush everything.
Do not attempt to execute all 5 days' worth of tests in 2 days (rushed execution with poor quality is worse than focused execution with clear documentation). Remove low-priority tests from the run formally.

Step 4: Document residual risk explicitly.
Write a brief risk memo:
"Due to the 2-day constraint, the following areas have NOT been tested: [list]. The identified risks associated with shipping without this coverage are: [list]. Risk acceptance sign-off is needed from [Product Owner/Manager] before release."

Step 5: Ensure smoke test and critical regression are included.
Even under time pressure, always run the smoke test (ensures build stability) and the most critical regression test cases (ensures the new feature has not broken existing functionality).

Step 6: Be honest in the Test Summary Report.
The test summary must accurately reflect what was tested and what was not. Do not sign off on coverage that was not achieved.`,
