    modelAnswer: `Requirement Traceability Matrix (RTM) is a document that maps every requirement to the test cases that verify it, and to any defects found against that requirement.

Purpose:
- Prove that every requirement has at least one test case (no gaps in coverage)
- Show which requirements have failing tests or open defects
- Justify the test scope to stakeholders
- Assess the impact of requirement changes (which test cases need updating)
- Support audit and compliance requirements

RTM Structure (basic columns):

  Req ID  | Requirement Description         | Test Case IDs      | Execution Status | Defect IDs
  REQ-001 | User can login with email       | TC-001, TC-002     | Pass             | —
  REQ-002 | User can reset password         | TC-003, TC-004     | Pass             | —
  REQ-003 | User account locks after 5 fail | TC-005             | Fail             | BUG-47
  REQ-004 | Admin can deactivate accounts   | TC-006, TC-007     | Not Run          | —

How to create:
1. List all requirements from the requirements document, user stories, or acceptance criteria
2. For each requirement, list all test cases written to verify it
3. As testing progresses, update execution status (Pass/Fail/Blocked/Not Run)
4. Link any defects found back to the requirement they violate

Forward Traceability: Starting from requirements — does every requirement have coverage? REQ-004 has test cases but they are "Not Run" — coverage gap to address.

Backward Traceability: Starting from test cases — does every test case trace to a valid requirement? If TC-008 has no requirement linked, it may be testing something not in scope, or a requirement that was never documented.

Practical tools: Excel spreadsheet (simple teams), Jira (Xray plugin links stories to test cases), TestRail (links test cases to requirements), Azure Test Plans (native requirement linkage).`,
