    difficulty: "Medium",
    question: "What is smoke testing versus sanity testing? When is each used in practice? What is the difference from regression testing?",
    hint: "Smoke = broad shallow build verification after every new build. Sanity = narrow deep check after a specific bug fix. Regression = full re-run of prior-passing tests after any change.",
    keyPoints: [
      "Smoke: shallow, wide, checks critical paths — is the build stable enough to test?",
      "Sanity: narrow, deep, checks a specific area after a fix — is this fix correct?",
      "Regression: broad re-run of all prior-passing tests — was anything else broken?",
      "Order in a cycle: new build → Smoke → Regression → Sanity (after specific fixes)",
    ],
    modelAnswer: `Smoke Testing, Sanity Testing, and Regression Testing — Differences:

Smoke Testing (Build Verification Test):
- When: After every new build is deployed to the test environment
- Scope: Broad and shallow — covers the most critical functional areas of the application
- Goal: Verify the build is stable enough to undergo full testing. "Does the application launch and can users perform core actions?"
- If smoke fails: Reject the build. Do not begin full testing on a broken build.
- Test case count: Typically 10-20 high-priority test cases
- Time: 30-60 minutes

Example smoke test cases for a banking app:
1. Application loads without error
2. User can log in with valid credentials
3. Account balance displays on the dashboard
4. Transfer funds page opens correctly
5. Logout works

Sanity Testing:
- When: After a specific bug has been fixed and a new build deployed
- Scope: Narrow and deep — focused only on the area that was fixed and directly related areas
- Goal: Verify this specific fix works correctly and has not broken the immediate surrounding functionality
- Does NOT cover the entire application — only the changed area
- Time: 15-60 minutes depending on complexity of the fix

Example: After fixing a bug where the "Forgot Password" link was not sending emails:
Sanity tests: Does "Forgot Password" now send the email? Does the reset link in the email work? Does the new password login work? Does the original login still work after reset?

Regression Testing:
- When: After any change to the codebase — new features, bug fixes, refactoring
- Scope: Broad — covers all previously passing test cases (or a risk-selected subset)
- Goal: Verify that changes have not unintentionally broken existing functionality
- Most time-consuming of the three
- Run after smoke passes and after all fixes for the current cycle are deployed

Sequence in a test cycle:
New build received → Smoke test (go/no-go gate) → Full testing → Fix deployed → Sanity test (fix verified) → Regression test (nothing else broken)`,
