    modelAnswer: `Healthcare Patient Management System — Testing Approach and Unique Concerns:

Unique Risks in Healthcare:
Patient safety is the primary concern — incorrect data (wrong medication, wrong dosage, wrong patient) can directly harm or kill patients. Unlike typical software, errors here have clinical consequences.

Functional Testing — Domain-Specific:

Patient Record Management:
- Creating, updating, and viewing patient records with correct personal and clinical data
- Name fields accept special characters (apostrophes, hyphens, accented characters — O'Brien, García)
- Date of birth validation: cannot be in the future; age must be consistent with entered DOB
- Allergy fields: drug allergies must be prominently displayed, not easily hidden
- Medication history: dose, frequency, and prescribing physician all stored correctly
- Clinical notes: save correctly, display in correct chronological order

Access Control and Role-Based Permissions:
- Doctors can view and update clinical notes; receptionists cannot
- Nurses can update vital signs; administrators cannot access clinical data
- Testing all role boundaries explicitly — what each role can and cannot do

Audit Trail:
- Every creation, update, and deletion of any patient data must create an immutable audit log entry including: user ID, timestamp, what changed, before and after values
- Audit log cannot be edited or deleted by any user (including administrators)
- Deletion of a patient record may be legally prohibited — test that "delete" actually archives, not destroys

HL7/FHIR Integration:
- Data exchanged with other healthcare systems (labs, radiology, pharmacy) in HL7 FHIR format
- Test that lab results received via HL7 messages are mapped to the correct patient record
- Test error handling when an incoming HL7 message is malformed or contains a patient ID not in the system

Data Integrity and Concurrency:
- Two clinicians editing the same patient record simultaneously must not result in data loss — conflict resolution must be tested
- No silent data loss when saving large clinical documents

Privacy and Security (HIPAA/GDPR):
- Patient data encrypted at rest and in transit
- Users cannot view records of patients they are not assigned to (patient-clinician assignment model)
- User sessions expire after a defined inactivity period (common requirement: 15 minutes in clinical settings)
- Export and print functions generate audit log entries
- Data minimisation: system does not collect or display data beyond what is clinically necessary

Regulatory and Compliance:
- Consent management: patient consent to data processing recorded and auditable
- Right to access (GDPR): patient can request their complete data export
- Prescribed data retention periods: records not deleted before legal minimum retention

Usability in Clinical Settings:
- Critical information (allergies, active medications) must be visible without scrolling
- Alert fatigue: if the system generates too many non-critical alerts, clinicians start dismissing them — test that alerts are meaningful and correctly prioritised
- The system must be operable with clinical gloves on (touch targets appropriately sized)`,
