    difficulty: "Medium",
    question: "What is test data management? How do you create, maintain, and protect test data in a professional testing environment?",
    hint: "Test data management covers creating representative data, handling sensitive/PII data, maintaining data across test cycles, and refreshing environments with production-like data.",
    keyPoints: [
      "Synthetic test data: generated data that looks real but is not",
      "Data masking/anonymisation: real production data with PII removed",
      "Test data for all partitions: valid, invalid, boundary, edge cases",
      "Data refresh strategy: clean state before each test cycle",
      "GDPR/HIPAA: production data cannot be used directly in test environments",
    ],
    modelAnswer: `Test Data Management covers the creation, maintenance, and protection of data used during testing.

Why test data matters:
Inadequate test data is one of the most common causes of low test coverage. If your test data only includes standard cases, you will miss boundary, edge, and negative scenarios.

Types of test data:

1. Synthetic (fabricated) data:
Created specifically for testing — realistic but not real. Contains edge cases, boundary values, and invalid inputs that real data might not include.
Example: Generating 10,000 customer records with names from many different countries (testing encoding), age values at the 18 and 65 year boundaries (testing discount tiers), and accounts with zero-balance, negative-balance, and maximum-balance values.

2. Anonymised/masked production data:
Real production data with PII (personally identifiable information) replaced by realistic but fake values.
Real name "John Smith" → "Alex Johnson" (same format, different value)
Real email "john@example.com" → "alex@testdomain.com"
Real card number → "4111111111111111" (Luhn-valid test card)
This gives production-representative data volumes and patterns without privacy risk.

Data coverage per test scenario:
For each input field, test data must cover:
- Valid values within range (EP valid partition)
- Boundary values (BVA min-1, min, min+1, max-1, max, max+1)
- Invalid values (EP invalid partitions)
- Special characters, Unicode, null, empty

GDPR and HIPAA compliance:
Real production data must NEVER be used directly in a test environment without anonymisation. This is a legal requirement under GDPR (EU) and HIPAA (US healthcare). A data breach from a test environment containing real PII carries the same legal consequences as a production breach.

Data refresh strategy:
Before each major test cycle, restore the test environment to a known clean baseline state. This ensures test cases start from the same preconditions every time and prevents data pollution from previous test runs interfering with current results.

Tools: Faker (library for generating synthetic data in multiple languages), SQL scripts for bulk data generation, Tonic.ai / Delphix for production data masking, Redgate Data Masker.`,
