    modelAnswer: `STAR Format Response:

Situation:
During a sprint at a fintech startup, I was assigned to test a new "instant top-up" feature for a prepaid card. The user story said "Users can top up their card balance instantly using a debit card." There were no acceptance criteria, no amount limits specified, no error scenarios documented, and no information about what "instantly" meant technically.

Task:
I needed to test this feature within the 3-day sprint window while also raising the risk of unclear requirements with the team.

Action:
I did not simply start testing with my own assumptions. First, I requested a Three Amigos session with the developer and Product Owner. In 30 minutes, we surfaced and resolved 8 ambiguities:
- Minimum and maximum top-up amounts (£5 minimum, £500 maximum per transaction)
- "Instantly" meant balance reflected within 5 seconds
- What happens if the debit card is declined (show an error, do not partial-debit)
- Can a user top up multiple times in one day? (Yes, up to £1,000 daily limit)
- What is shown on the user's bank statement?

I documented all agreed acceptance criteria in the Jira story before writing any test cases, and got the Product Owner's written confirmation in the Jira comments.

I then wrote 22 test cases covering the agreed scenarios, including boundary values (£5, £500 limits), daily limit, various decline reasons, and the "instantly" response time requirement.

Result:
I found 3 defects in the first execution pass — including one where the balance update took 8 seconds instead of 5, and one where a declined card showed a generic "error" message instead of the required specific reason.

What I changed going forward: I added "test case review against acceptance criteria" as a mandatory step in my pre-execution checklist, and began advocating for Three Amigos sessions as a sprint planning standard.`,
