    difficulty: "Hard",
    question: "Explain the concept of defect clustering (Pareto Principle in testing). How do you use it to focus your testing effort?",
    hint: "The Pareto Principle in testing: approximately 80% of defects are found in 20% of modules. Identify defect-dense modules through defect history and focus testing there.",
    keyPoints: [
      "80% of defects typically reside in 20% of modules",
      "Defect clustering: some modules are historically more defect-prone",
      "Use defect history to identify high-defect-density modules",
      "Pesticide paradox: repeating the same tests finds fewer new bugs over time",
      "Rotate test approaches and add new test cases to combat the pesticide paradox",
    ],
    modelAnswer: `Defect Clustering and the Pareto Principle in Software Testing:

The Pareto Principle (80/20 rule) applied to testing: empirical studies show that approximately 80% of defects are concentrated in approximately 20% of modules. This is called defect clustering.

Why does defect clustering occur?
- Some modules are inherently more complex (more logic paths, more integrations)
- Some modules were written by less experienced developers or under time pressure
- Some areas have changed frequently (frequent changes introduce regressions)
- Some areas were poorly specified (ambiguous requirements generate more implementation errors)

How to identify defect-dense modules:
1. Analyse defect history: run a report in Jira showing defect count by module/component over the last 3-6 releases
2. Calculate defect density: defects per module / lines of code or function points in that module
3. Modules with consistently high defect density are your high-risk areas for future testing

Practical application:
If history shows that 15 of the last 20 defects have come from the Payment and Order Processing modules, those modules should receive:
- More thorough test coverage (more negative cases, boundary cases, edge cases)
- More frequent regression testing
- Earlier testing in the cycle (so defects are found when they are cheapest to fix)

Pesticide Paradox (a related testing principle):
If the same test cases are run repeatedly without adding new ones, they become less effective at finding new bugs over time — like using the same pesticide repeatedly, the "bugs" (software defects) become resistant.

How to address it:
- Regularly review and update the test suite — add new test cases based on recent defects, new code paths, and new usage patterns
- Use exploratory testing alongside scripted testing — exploratory testing finds what scripted tests cannot
- Rotate test approaches: someone who has always tested the login module will have blind spots that a new tester approaching it fresh will not have

Combining both principles: Focus more test cases on historically defect-dense modules (Pareto), but continuously add new test approaches to those modules (combat pesticide paradox).`,
