    difficulty: "Medium",
    question: "Your team is moving from Waterfall to Agile. How does your testing approach change? What challenges do you anticipate and how would you address them?",
    hint: "Cover: testing within sprints (not after), continuous feedback, automated regression need, shift-left, Definition of Done, and common pain points during the transition.",
    keyPoints: [
      "Testing moves from a dedicated phase to continuous activity within sprints",
      "Shift-left: testers involved from Sprint Planning, not just at the end",
      "Regression automation becomes critical — manual-only regression cannot keep up",
      "Three Amigos and DoD replace formal test entry/exit criteria",
      "Challenges: getting builds to test early enough in the sprint, no time for full regression",
    ],
    modelAnswer: `Waterfall to Agile Testing — Key Changes, Challenges, and Solutions:

How Testing Changes:

In Waterfall: Testing is a separate phase at the end of development. Testers receive a complete build and execute a full test plan. There is a formal handover between development and testing.

In Agile: Testing happens continuously within each sprint alongside development. A 2-week sprint means: stories are developed in days 1-8, tested in days 5-12 (overlapping with development), with defects fixed and retested in days 10-14. There is no formal handover — the team works together.

Key changes to testing practice:
1. Shift-left: Testers participate in Sprint Planning, Backlog Refinement, and Three Amigos sessions — providing input on requirements and testability before a single line of code is written.
2. Continuous testing: Test cases are written for each story in the same sprint as development, not after.
3. Definition of Done: Replaces formal exit criteria — every story must be tested and all acceptance criteria verified before it is called Done.
4. No more big-bang integration: Stories are tested individually and integrated continuously, so integration surprises are smaller and caught earlier.

Challenges and how to address them:

Challenge 1: Builds not ready to test until late in the sprint.
Solution: Establish a team agreement that stories must be deployed to the test environment by Day 7 of a 2-week sprint. Raise this as a blocker in Daily Standups if it is consistently violated.

Challenge 2: No time for full regression in each sprint.
Solution: This is the primary driver for test automation. Begin building an automated regression suite for stable, high-risk features. Until automation exists, use risk-based selective regression — not full regression — in each sprint.

Challenge 3: Testers feel "blocked" waiting for developers.
Solution: Plan testing tasks across multiple stories per sprint. While waiting for one story to be deployed, write test cases for the next story. Never be idle.

Challenge 4: Teams new to Agile skip testing to meet sprint velocity.
Solution: Enforce the Definition of Done. A story is not complete until QA has verified it. Work with the Scrum Master to make this a team norm from the first sprint.`,
