    id: "mt72",
    domain: "Manual Testing",
    type: "technical",
    difficulty: "Medium",
    question: "What are some common testing anti-patterns that reduce test effectiveness? How would you identify and fix them?",
    hint: "Anti-patterns: testing only the happy path, tests that never fail, lack of independence between test cases, testing implementation not behaviour, vague expected results.",
    keyPoints: [
      "Testing only happy path — misses all failure and edge cases",
      "Tests that never fail — provides false confidence",
      "Dependent test cases — failures cascade and obscure root cause",
      "Testing implementation not behaviour — tests break on refactoring",
      "Copy-paste test cases without updating — outdated coverage",
    ],
    modelAnswer: `Common Testing Anti-Patterns and How to Fix Them:

1. Happy Path Only Testing:
Anti-pattern: Test cases cover only the successful scenario. No negative, boundary, or edge cases.
Why harmful: Most production defects come from error handling, boundary conditions, and unusual inputs.
Fix: For every feature, explicitly write at least one negative test case and one boundary value test case before considering coverage complete.

2. Tests That Never Fail (Ice Cream Cone Anti-pattern):
Anti-pattern: The test always passes because the expected result is too vague ("page loads correctly") or the test is checking the wrong thing.
Why harmful: Provides false confidence — the tests look green but would not catch a real defect.
Fix: Review test cases with this question: "If I deliberately introduced a bug here, would this test catch it?" If not, rewrite the expected result to be specific and observable.

3. Test Case Dependency:
Anti-pattern: Test TC-002 only works correctly if TC-001 ran first and left data in the system.
Why harmful: When TC-001 fails, TC-002, TC-003, and TC-004 all fail in a cascade, obscuring the real root cause. Tests cannot be run in isolation.
Fix: Each test case must set up its own preconditions explicitly and clean up after itself. Use independent test data per test case.

4. Testing Implementation Instead of Behaviour:
Anti-pattern: Tests verify internal implementation details (which function was called, which database query ran) rather than observable behaviour (what the user sees, what the API returns).
Why harmful: When the code is refactored (same behaviour, different implementation), all tests break even though the feature still works correctly.
Fix: Test the observable output and user-facing behaviour. Leave internal implementation to unit tests written by developers.

5. Copy-Paste Test Cases Without Updating:
Anti-pattern: Test cases for a new feature are copied from a similar existing feature and the expected results are not fully updated.
Why harmful: Tests may be checking the wrong outcomes, or may pass when they should fail.
Fix: Review every test case before execution. Any test case copied from another context must be explicitly reviewed and updated.

6. Outdated Test Suite:
Anti-pattern: Test cases for features that were removed 6 months ago are still in the suite and are executed in every regression run.
Why harmful: Wastes time, clutters reports, and creates noise that distracts from real failures.
Fix: Conduct quarterly test suite audits. Remove test cases for removed features. Update test cases for changed features.

7. Ignoring Failing Tests:
Anti-pattern: Some tests in the regression suite are known to be "flaky" (fail intermittently) and are simply ignored or re-run until they pass.
Why harmful: Trains the team to ignore test failures — eventually a real failure is ignored too.
Fix: Fix or quarantine flaky tests immediately. A test that cannot be trusted is worse than no test.`,
